{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:44:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17100"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17100"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9790"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70075"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9790"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55538"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5107"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23183"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23521"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70075","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70075"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is diagnosed with Graves\u0027 disease. The endocrinologist is considering starting antithyroid medication. Treatment with carbimazole is being considered and the doctor will counsel the patient on the side-effects and potential risks of this medication.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important safety consideration to discuss?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Risk of permanent hypothyroidism","Risk of birth defects if pregnancy occurs","Risk of aplastic anaemia","Risk of hepatic dysfunction","Risk of thyroid storm"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most important consideration is the \u003Cstrong\u003Erisk of birth defects if pregnancy occurs\u003C/strong\u003E. Carbimazole is highly teratogenic, particularly during the first trimester of pregnancy. Potential birth defects include aplasia cutis, choanal atresia, tracheo-oesophageal fistula, and developmental delay.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk of permanent hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is not a major concern as hypothyroidism from carbimazole is typically reversible when the medication is stopped.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk of aplastic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare but serious side effect of carbimazole, but teratogenicity is the primary concern in this case given the patient\u0027s age and reproductive status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk of hepatic dysfunction\u003C/strong\u003E is a less common side effect and not the main safety concern for a woman of childbearing age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERisk of thyroid storm\u003C/strong\u003E is a complication of untreated hyperthyroidism, not a risk of carbimazole therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWomen of childbearing potential should be counselled about the teratogenic risks of carbimazole and advised to use effective contraception. If pregnancy is desired or occurs, switching to propylthiouracil is recommended as it has a lower risk of causing birth defects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbimazole is a teratogenic medication that can cause serious birth defects if taken during pregnancy, especially in the first trimester.","Women of childbearing age taking carbimazole must use effective contraception and should be counselled about pregnancy risks.","Propylthiouracil is the preferred antithyroid medication during pregnancy due to lower teratogenic risk."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55538"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17100"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55538"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T16:59:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T17:00:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9790"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70075"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici